Geospatial Risk Prediction in Chicago IL

By Stephanie Onuaja

October 27, 2022

0.1 Introduction

Using geospatial risk modeling tools commonly referred to as “predictive policing”, I built a model to forecast the risk of criminal property damage in Chicago. Predictive Policing is a set of algorithms that have been employed by the public sector to predict the location, and the doer of crime as well as the judicial response to crime.

With the assumption that crime is a function of exposure to a series of geospatial risk and protective factors, two features were added to the model that accounts for the risk factors that impact and increase crime risk. This model will explore the spatial risk factors that would increase the risk of a property being damaged.

Due to the perpetuated discriminatory and disproportionate policing that targets Black and Brown neighborhoods, it is inherent that recorded crime would reflect the criminalization of some communities and races more than others. Thus, the predictions of future crime risk would be biased and could reproduce the dangerous policing measures that over-police communities of color.

0.1.0.1 Setup

Using data from the City of Chicago’s Open Data Portal, I pulled data on police districts, police beats, criminal property damage, and the city’s boundary.

0.1.0.2 Visualizing Property Damage in Point Form and Density Plot

I decided to look at criminal property damage. Selection bias would arise because the data would be limited to reported cases, so it may not fully represent where the crimes are occurring. From the density plots, we see that most of the reported cases are in West Chicago and South Chicago.

grid.arrange(ncol=2,
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = chicagoBoundary, fill = "grey40") +
  geom_sf(data = Damages, colour="#41dbf7", size=0.1, show.legend = "point") +
  labs(title= "Criminal Property Damage, Points", 
       subtitle= "Chicago, IL") +
  mapTheme(title_size = 14),

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = chicagoBoundary, fill = "grey40") +
  stat_density2d(data = data.frame(st_coordinates(Damages)), 
                 aes(X, Y, fill = ..level.., alpha = ..level..),
                 size = 0.01, bins = 40, geom = 'polygon') +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  scale_alpha(range = c(0.00, 0.35), guide = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Density of Criminal Property Damage", 
       subtitle= "Chicago, IL") +

0.2 Data Wrangling

0.2.0.1 Creating a Fishnet Grid

The fishnet grid is created from Chicago’s boundary with a cell size of 500 by 500 meters. The points of property damage were aggregated to the fishnet by taking the sum of points in each grid cell.

fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(chicagoBoundary,
               cellsize = 500, 
               square = TRUE) %>%
  .[chicagoBoundary] %>%           
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = 1:n())

# Aggregate Damages to Property Points to the Fishnet
crime_net <- 
  dplyr::select(Damages) %>% 
  mutate(countDamages = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countDamages = replace_na(countDamages, 0),
         uniqueID = 1:n(),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), 
                       size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, aes(fill = countDamages), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis() + 
  labs(title = "Count of Criminal Damages for the fishnet") +
  mapTheme(title_size = 14)

0.2.0.2 Modeling Spatial Features

I selected noise complaints and affordable housing rental developments as potential spatial risk factors that could impact the occurrence of criminal property damage.

Noise <- 
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Environment-Sustainable-Development/CDPH-Environmental-Complaints/fypr-ksnz") %>% 
    mutate(year = substr(complaint_date,1,4)) %>%  filter(year == "2018") %>% 
    filter(complaint_type == "NOISE COMPLAINT")%>%
    dplyr::select(Y = latitude, X = longitude) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant") %>%
    st_transform(st_crs(fishnet)) %>%
    mutate(Legend = "Noise_Complaints")

AfforHousing <- 
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Community-Economic-Development/Affordable-Rental-Housing-Developments/s6ha-ppgi") %>%  
    dplyr::select(Y = latitude, X = longitude) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant") %>%
    st_transform(st_crs(fishnet)) %>%
    mutate(Legend = "Affordable_Housing")

neighborhoods <- 
  st_read("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/blackmad/neighborhoods/master/chicago.geojson")%>%
  st_transform(st_crs(fishnet)) 
## Reading layer `chicago' from data source 
##   `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/blackmad/neighborhoods/master/chicago.geojson' 
##   using driver `GeoJSON'
## Simple feature collection with 98 features and 4 fields
## Geometry type: MULTIPOLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -87.94011 ymin: 41.64454 xmax: -87.52414 ymax: 42.02304
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84

# Aggregate a feature to our fishnet

vars_net <- 
  rbind(Noise, AfforHousing) %>%
  st_join(., fishnet, join=st_within) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(uniqueID, Legend) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
    full_join(fishnet) %>%
    spread(Legend, count, fill=0) %>%
    st_sf() %>%
    dplyr::select(-`<NA>`) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    ungroup()

0.3 Feature Engineering

0.3.0.1 Nearest Neighbor Features

The nearest neighbor feature converts the grid cells into centroids and measures to k risk factor points. (k=3)

st_c    <- st_coordinates
st_coid <- st_centroid

## create NN from noise and affordable housing units
vars_net <- vars_net %>%
    mutate(Noise.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(Noise),
                                           k = 3))
   vars_net <- vars_net %>%
     mutate(AfforHousing.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                          st_c(AfforHousing),3))

vars_net.long.nn <- 
  dplyr::select(vars_net, ends_with(".nn")) %>%
    gather(Variable, value, -geometry)
# Visualizing NN features    
vars <- unique(vars_net.long.nn$Variable)
mapList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  mapList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(vars_net.long.nn, Variable == i), aes(fill=value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 10)}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(mapList, ncol = 2, top = "Nearest Neighbor Risk Factors by Fishnet")) 

final_net <-
  left_join(crime_net, st_drop_geometry(vars_net), by="uniqueID") 

### Join in areal data
final_net <-
  st_centroid(final_net) %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(neighborhoods, name), by = "uniqueID") %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(policeDistricts, District), by = "uniqueID") %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(dplyr::select(final_net, geometry, uniqueID)) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
  na.omit()
## Joining, by = "uniqueID"

0.3.0.2 Measure Distance to One Point

The distance to Chicago’s Central Business District (the Loop) was measured.

loopPoint <-
  filter(neighborhoods, name == "Loop") %>%
  st_centroid()

vars_net$loopDistance =
  st_distance(st_centroid(vars_net),loopPoint) %>%
  as.numeric() 
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = vars_net, aes(fill = loopDistance ), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis() + 
  labs(title = "Euclidean Distance to The Loop") +
  mapTheme(title_size = 14)

0.3.0.3 Local Moran’s I

The Local Moran’s describes the local spatial process of criminal property damage. That is how property damage counts relate to their neighbors.

# Weights 
final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)

final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

# Local Moran's I
local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countDamages, final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# join local Moran's I results to fishnet
final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(countDamages = countDamages, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

The relatively high values of I on the map represent strong and statistically significant evidence of local clustering. The smaller the p-value the more significant the clusters.


vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 10) + theme(legend.position="bottom")}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Morans I statistics, Property Damage"))

0.3.0.4 Distance to Hot spot

This map shows the average nearest neighbor distance from each cell centroid to its nearest significant cluster.


final_net <- final_net %>% 
  mutate(Damages.isSig = 
           ifelse(local_morans[,5] <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(Damages.isSig.dist = 
           nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)),
                       st_c(st_coid(filter(final_net, 
                                           Damages.isSig == 1))), k = 1))
### Plot NN distance to hot spot
ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = final_net, aes(fill=Damages.isSig.dist), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="Damages.isSig.dist") +
      labs(title="Distance to highly significant property damage hotspots") +
      mapTheme(title_size = 14)

0.3.0.5 Correlation Plots

The correlation plots begin to show how well the spatial risk features would predict criminal property damage.

correlation.long <-
  st_drop_geometry(final_net) %>%
    dplyr::select(-uniqueID, -cvID, -name, -District) %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -countDamages)

correlation.cor <-
  correlation.long %>%
    group_by(Variable) %>%
    summarize(correlation = cor(Value, countDamages, use = "complete.obs"))
ggplot(correlation.long, aes(Value, countDamages)) +
  geom_point(size = 0.1) +
  geom_text(data = correlation.cor, aes(label = paste("r =", round(correlation, 2))),
            x=-Inf, y=Inf, vjust = 1.5, hjust = -.1) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "blue") +
  facet_wrap(~Variable, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Property Damage count as a function of risk factors") +
  plotTheme()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = final_net, aes(countDamages))+
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, color = 'black', fill = "#277e8e") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 80, by = 15)) +
  labs(title = 'Distribution of Criminal Property Damage')+plotTheme()

  dataset = final_net,

  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv,           Error = Prediction - countDamages,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = Prediction - countDamages,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process"),
    
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = Prediction - countDamages,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),

While there are areas where the high density of observed property damage overlays high-risk categories, some of the density also occur in lower-risk categories which may suggest latent risk or a poorly fit model.

rbind(dam_KDE_sf, dam_risk_sf) %>%

The table below confirms that the model is poorly fitted. The model showed that Kernel Density captured a greater share of 2018 damaged properties in the highest risk category relative to risk predictions.

0.5 Conclusion

I would not recommend my algorithm to predict the risk of criminal property damage in Chicago for the following reasons. The model is limited to the reported cases of damaged property which implies that we do not see the full picture. The predictions may be inclined toward the areas with previously reported cases. Additionally, the spatial risk factors selected in this model were limited in their ability to predict property damage. A more robust selection of spatial risk factors could improve the performance of this model.

However, even if we assume that all cases of criminal property damage were reported, the accuracy of the predictions could still be questioned. Unlike crimes such as robbery whose potential risk may be influenced by the area the person is in, property damage is often connected to other crimes or is targeted at a particular person. In that case, the location of the house does not necessarily determine if a house would be damaged.

Finally, models like this one used in predictive policing can produce dangerous outcomes in our communities. Even without the indenting to, they can reproduce systems of discrimination that manifest in the way we police black and Brown neighborhoods. They could be better adapted to other uses by the public sector.
